author: GourmetFilet
body:
yeah this shit started as something i tried myself and i quickly realized, nah ima fuck this shit up and called some pros lol. 

Had a bath/shower that was constantly leaking from the faucet. Thought I would take the the faucet  off and replace them and the valve. Took em off, could see behind the wall and my copper pipe hook ups were beyond shot. didnt do shit to them. next day I woke up to water all over my first floor BR floor. WTF. Shut the water off, had a plumber come out and say my entire bath/shower and cold water line for the whole house needed replaced for 12K. 2nd guy said the same shit but for 10K, and same with the 3rd guy. 

4th guy came out and said nah fam. let me sharkbite this shit, weld this shit, add this shit and ill reglaze your tub and redo tile on walls for $3.4K. fuck yes. 

There is no way in hell I would be able to do this kind of shit my self lol

author: StonksMcGee
body: Yup, my mistake, they are not issuers, only Disc and Amex do their own issuing. Payments processors DO NOT have a high margin at all. I used to work for one for over 10 years, and yes they do make money but it’s not because of high margin, instead high volume. High volume of transactions going through a processor = decent money. Margins are low. You also have to keep in mind that they most likely do not do their own processing and outsource it to a platform like Global Payments or First Data who charge an interchange fee (base cost). The third party provider (USIO) then pads the interchange by adding a few basis points to it and that’s where money is made on a transaction. Payments processors sometimes make money on fees (statement fees, PCI compliance fees, etc). Anyway, do what you feel, it’s your money, but remember, buy the hype, sell the news. It seems u/varun22486 or whatever already “took profits” so you should do the same if you’re in the money. If not, wait for the earnings and keep your fingers crossed. This is a small shop in a market where competition is extremely high to say the least. Holding and hoping for this to reach Square levels is a moonshot. Your dime, not mine, just trying to help.

you missed Dimon's update:

>In January, Dimon walked back his criticism of the cryptocurrency space, when he called bitcoin investors "stupid" and said they would "pay the price for it one day." The CEO, who once indicated that he would fire any of the bank's employees who were caught trading bitcoin, expressed optimism regarding the underlying blockchain technology in an interview with Fox in January. He added that he is "open-minded" about cryptocurrencies, if they are "properly controlled and regulated." In October, JPM announced a blockchain-powered system intended to "significantly reduce" the number of parties needed to verify global payments and cut transaction times from weeks to hours. [source](https://www.investopedia.com/news/jpmorgan-dives-crypto-space/)

Bitcoin replaces banks. So of course the bankers are gonna talk trash. Its like Blockbuster saying Netflix's movie streaming will never go nowhere.

author: SleepyRevenant
body:
I work as a  data engineering consultant and I assure you, you can just port some dated corporate oracle/IBM setup to hadoop/kafka/spark/<whatever db the CTO likes the sound of> and make serious money doing it. Anything that can be done with data can be done (and is best done) with java/scala or a python interface for java/scala.

So apart from web frameworks (where spring is an option) and REST APIs (Just use a fucking JDBC) what exactly is so immensely resource intensive server side that you absolutely must use non-JVM compiled code for? Let's not forget that all important Python packages are readily available for ARM architecture so interpreted shit clearly isn't the problem.

I bet you're a ruby developer who thinks that your dying language is somehow not going to go the way of PHP.
